versial reforms. Newton's analysis reveals how rival descriptions of immigrant groups and the flattering or disparaging myths that surround them define, shape, and can ultimately determine fights over immigration policy. Her pathbreaking findings will shed new light on the current political battles, their likely outcomes, and where to go from here.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyxUnited States. 0aImmigrantsxUnited States. 4a1980s. 4a1990s. 4aBeginning. 4aLina. 4aNewton. 4aclose. 4acontroversial. 4adisputes. 4afrom. 4aillegal. 4aimmigrants. 4aintroduction. 4alegislators. 4alook. 4anegativefacilitated. 4aoverwhelmingly. 4apassing. 4aportrayals. 4apositive. 4areforms. 4areveals. 4ashift. 4awith. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814759028.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK